{"key":"post-13800985","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>13800985</id>\n<content>It sounds like you have a really good pressure cooker.&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;My AA75X sterilizers pull a good vacuum after they cool down too.&amp;nbsp; I let the Pressure cooker cool to nearly room temperature, and then set it in front of the flow hood before I pop the valve to allow air to enter.&amp;nbsp; If you don't have a flow hood, try laying a clean, damp towel over the opening.&amp;nbsp; This should help filter the air as it enters.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;You're right not to over-challenge your jar filters.&amp;nbsp; Nature abhors a vacuum, so that air is going to equalize the pressure everywhere, and that means your jars will get an influx too.&amp;nbsp; As an added measure, make sure your jar lids are on very tight, so that any air entering will be forced through the filters.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>13800997</next>\n<prev>13800984</prev>\n<first>13800926</first>\n<last>13801005</last>\n<when>1295274756</when>\n<utime>01/17/11 04:32 PM</utime>\n</post>"}